I den hÃ¤r uppgiften ska ni skriva objektorienterad kod. Er kod ska

  1. Definera en superklass Customer med fÃ¤lten name och email och med den oimplementerade metoden send_newsletter (se exempel med n_wheels nedan).
  2. Definera tvÃ¥ subklasser, RegularCustomer och PremiumCustomer, som implementerar send_newsletter genom att skriva ut (print) fÃ¶ljande strÃ¤ngar:

UtgÃ¥ frÃ¥n Python exemplet fÃ¶r att skriva er kod, och R exemplet lÃ¤ngre ned fÃ¶r att se hur utskrifterna ska se ut. Observera skillnaden i koden, R Ã¤r inte ett objektorienterat sprÃ¥k utan anvÃ¤nder istÃ¤llet funktioner.

Exempel Python

I det hÃ¤r exemplet ser vi hur subklassen Bike skapas genom att Ã¤rva superklassen Vehicle och implementera funktionen n_wheels som returnerar antalet hjul fordonet har. FÃ¶r att komma Ã¥t fÃ¤lt och metoder inom en instans av en klass, dvs. en realisation av klassen, anvÃ¤nder vi punkt, .. Notera att . # Define super class Vehicle
class Vehicle:
    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name
    
    # Define function returning the number of wheels of the vehicle
    def n_wheels(self):
        raise NotImplementedError("Subclass must implement this method")

# Defining Bike class, inheriting from Vehicle
class Bike(Vehicle):
    def n_wheels(self):
        return 2
    
bike = Bike("Crescent")
# Using the dot, ., to access class fields
bike.name
'Crescent'
# Using the dot, ., to access class method
bike.n_wheels()
2

Exempel R

Den hÃ¤r koden Ã¥stadkommer det ni ska gÃ¶ra i Python, men i R. R Ã¤r ett âfunctional programming languageâ och har stÃ¶der inte OOP naturligt, istÃ¤llet mÃ¥ste funktioner anvÃ¤ndas. Observera att ni ska utgÃ¥ frÃ¥n Python-koden ovan och ni behÃ¶ver inte fÃ¶rstÃ¥ R koden i sin helhet, bara observera utskrifterna lÃ¤ngst ned.

# Define the Customer 'class'
Customer <- function(name, email) {
    list(
      name = name,
      email = email,
      send_newsletter = function() {
        stop("send_newsletter() needs to be defined in the subclass.")
      }
    )
}

# Define the RegularCustomer 'subclass'
RegularCustomer <- function(name, email) {
    customer <- Customer(name, email)
    customer$send_newsletter <- function() {
      cat(sprintf("[mailto:%s]Dear %s, check out our weekly deals!\n", customer$email, customer$name))
    }
    customer
}

# Define the PremiumCustomer 'subclass'
PremiumCustomer <- function(name, email) {
    customer <- Customer(name, email)
    customer$send_newsletter <- function() {
      cat(sprintf("[mailto:%s]Dear %s, enjoy exclusive premium offers and discounts!\n", customer$email, customer$name))
    }
    customer
}

# Example usage
customers <- list(
    RegularCustomer("Alex", "alex@example.com"), 
    PremiumCustomer("Jordan", "jordan@example.com")
)

for (customer in customers) {
    customer$send_newsletter()
}

[mailto:jordan@example.com]Dear Jordan, enjoy exclusive premium offers and discounts!

set.seed(42)
n_replicates <- 1000
sample_sizes <- c(5, 10, 30)

# Storing in tibble, slow, but neat for plotting results
results <- tibble(
    sample_size = integer(0),
    replicate = integer(0),
    mean = numeric(0),
    distribution = character(0)
)
for (sample_size in sample_sizes)
{
    for (replicate in 1:n_replicates)
    {
        mu_norm <- mean(rnorm(sample_size, 2, 1))
        mu_exp <- mean(rexp(sample_size, 0.5))
        results <- rbind(
            results,
            data.frame(
                sample_size = sample_size,
                replicate = replicate,
                mean = mu_norm,
                distribution = "norm"),
            data.frame(
                sample_size = sample_size,
                replicate = replicate,
                mean = mu_exp,
                distribution = "exp"))
    }
}
results |> 
    ggplot(aes(x = mean, col = distribution, fill = distribution)) + 
    geom_density(alpha = 0.3) +
    facet_wrap(~ sample_size, scales = "free") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 2, linetype = 2, col = "black") +
    labs(
        x = "Mean",
        col = "Distribution",
        fill = "Distribution") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(
    axis.text.y = element_blank(),
    axis.title.y = element_blank(),
    axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
    legend.position = "top")
